:"about 1221","1156":"1156","1199":"1199","1221":"1221","1219":"1219","1229":"1229","Huddersfield, , West Yorkshire, England":"Huddersfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Of,, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Drakes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Drake  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: habitational name from Drax (Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>dræg</i> ‘portage, place where boats are dragged’ or <i>dræg</i> ‘drag net’, influenced by Old Norse <i>drag</i> ‘portage’, with a plural <i>drages</i> being shortened to <i>drags</i>, <i>Drax</i>.","In some cases perhaps an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) cognate in some other language."],"variants":[{"name":"Drake","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>drake</i>, either ‘drake, male duck’ (compare   Duck  ) or ‘dragon’ (Old English <i>draca</i> ‘snake, dragon’ or the cognate Old Norse <i>draki</i>), including an emblematic dragon on a flag (compare   Dragon  ). Both the Old English and the Old Norse forms are from Latin <i>draco</i> ‘snake, monster’; its sense as a nickname is unclear but it may have had the sense ‘standard bearer’. The name was taken to Ireland in the 13th century and reinforced by later English settlers in the 17th century.","German: from Low German <i>drake</i> ‘dragon’, familiar as image on signboards, hence a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn with such signboard.","Dutch: variant, mostly Americanized and Flemish, of <b>Draak</b>, a cognate of 2 above, from <i>draak</i> (Middle Dutch <i>drake</i>) ‘dragon’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Captain John Drakes was born in 1187, in Huddersfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Geoffery Drakes, was 31 and his mother, Mrs., was 27. He married Margery FitzJohn in 1216, in Huddersfield, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1229, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1187–1229":"1187–1229","1191–Female":"1191–Surnud","1217–Male":"1217–Surnud","1219–Male":"1219–Surnud","1221–Male":"1221–Surnud","1223–Female":"1223–Surnud","1156–1199":"1156–1199","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1187":"1187","1186":"1186","Abt 1219":"umbes 1219","1160":"1160","1191":"1191","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","Abt 1223":"umbes 1223","1223":"1223","Abt 1221":"umbes 1221","1156":"1156","1199":"1199","1221":"1221","1219":"1219","1229":"1229","Huddersfield, , West Yorkshire, England":"Huddersfield, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of,, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1187–1229":"1187–1229","1191–Female":"1191–Kuollut","1217–Male":"1217–Kuollut","1219–Male":"1219–Kuollut","1221–Male":"1221–Kuollut","1223–Female":"1223–Kuollut","1156–1199":"1156–1199","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1187":"1187","1186":"1186","Abt 1219":"noin 1219","1160":"1160","1191":"1191","1217":"1217","1216":"1216","Abt 1223":"noin 1223","1223":"1223","Abt 1221":"noin 1221","1156":"1156","1199":"1199","1221":"1221","1219":"1219","1229":"1229","Huddersfield, , West Yorkshire, England":"Huddersfield, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of,, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1187–1229":"1187–1229","1191–Female":"1191–Décédée","1217–Male":"1217–Décédé","1219–Male":"1219–Décédé","1221–Male":"1221–Décédé","1223–Female":"1223–Décédée","1156–1199":"1156–1199","1160–Female":"1160–Décédée","1187